1. What are Selectors? Explain every type.
Selectors are used to select HTML elements to apply CSS.

✔ Types of Selectors:

Universal Selector – *
Selects all elements.

Element Selector – p, h1, div
Selects by tag name.

ID Selector – #idname
Selects element with specific id.

Class Selector – .classname
Selects elements with class.

Group Selector – h1, p, div
Applies same style to multiple elements.

Attribute Selector – input[type="text"]
Selects elements by attribute.

Pseudo-class Selector – :hover, :focus
Selects based on state.

Pseudo-element Selector – ::before, ::after
Selects part of an element.

2. Difference between Pseudo-Element & Pseudo-Class selectors
✔ Pseudo-class (:)

Works based on state
Example:
:hover, :active, :focus

✔ Pseudo-element (::)

Selects part of the element
Example:
::before, ::after, ::first-line, ::selection

3. Difference between em unit & rem unit
em
Relative to parent element font-size.

rem
Relative to root element (html) font-size.

rem is more predictable.

4. What are CSS functions?
Functions in CSS perform specific tasks.
Examples:

calc() → Performs calculations
rgb() / hsl() → Colors
url() → For images
var() → For CSS variables
min(), max(), clamp() → Responsive sizing

5. What is CSS Box Model & what are its elements?
Box model consists of:
Content
Padding
Border
Margin
Used to control layout & spacing.

6. What is float property of CSS?
float moves an element left or right, allowing text to wrap around it.
Used mostly for layout before flexbox.

7. Difference between flex & grid
✔ Flexbox
One dimension (row OR column)
Best for alignment

✔ Grid
Two dimensions (rows AND columns)
Best for layout design / complex structure

8. What are the flexbox properties & flex-item properties?
▶ Flex Container Properties

display: flex
flex-direction
justify-content
align-items
align-content
flex-wrap

▶ Flex Item Properties

flex-grow
flex-shrink
flex-basis
align-self
order

9. What are Position properties? Explain z-index.
✔ Position Values:

static – default
relative – moves relative to itself
absolute – positioned inside nearest positioned parent
fixed – sticks to viewport
sticky – switches between relative & fixed

✔ z-index
Controls stacking order (which element comes on top).

10. Difference between:
(i) Position Fixed vs Sticky

Fixed

Always fixed on the screen
Does not move on scroll
Sticky
Acts relative
Becomes fixed when reaching scroll threshold

(ii) Absolute vs Relative

Relative
Moves relative to itself
Still occupies space
Absolute
Removed from normal flow
Positioned relative to nearest ancestor

11. Difference between: visibility:hidden & display:none
Property	Element Visible?	Space Occupied?
display:none	No	No
visibility:hidden	No	Yes

12. Explain overflow property
Controls what happens when content overflows.

Values:

visible → default
hidden → cuts overflow
scroll → always shows scrollbar
auto → scrollbar only if needed

13. What is the work of !important?
Overrides all other CSS rules.
Highest priority.

Example:
color: red !important;

14. What are the transform properties we have?
Common transform functions:

rotate()
scale()
translate()
skew()
matrix()
perspective()

Used for animations & effects.
